<p>Futarasan Shrine is the oldest religious site in Nikko, founded in 767 by the monk Shodo Shonin. This Shinto shrine is dedicated to the three mountain deities of Nikko: Mt. Nantai, Mt. Nyoho, and Mt. Taro, which are considered sacred.</p>

            <div class="highlight">
                <strong>Hours:</strong> Apr-Oct 8:00-17:00, Nov-Mar 9:00-16:00 (entry closes 30 min before)<br>
                <strong>Admission:</strong> Main area free, Garden ¥300 for adults, ¥100 for students
            </div>

            <div class="highlight">
                The shrine's grounds encompass all of Nikko's sacred mountains and Lake Chuzenji, making it one of Japan's largest shrine precincts.
            </div>

<p>Unlike the ornate Toshogu Shrine nearby, Futarasan maintains a more traditional Shinto aesthetic with simple, elegant wooden structures that harmonize with the natural forest setting. The shrine represents the ancient Japanese belief in the spiritual power of mountains and natural landscapes.</p>

<p>The shrine complex includes several important structures: the main hall (honden), worship hall (haiden), and the sacred Shinkyo Bridge. Visitors come here to pray for good fortune in marriage, family harmony, and protection from natural disasters, as the mountain deities are believed to watch over the region.</p>

<p>The shrine is particularly famous for its annual Yayoi Festival in April, one of the three great festivals of Nikko, featuring elaborate floats and traditional performances.</p>

